properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Porepunkah. 
  • This Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 7:43pm Friday, 29 August.
  • Victoria Police are searching for an armed and dangerous offender Desmond Freeman (Filby) in the area of Porepunkah.
  • Travel in the area should be restricted to essential activities only.
If you see Desmond Freeman (Filby), call 000 immediately and do not approach the offender. 
What you should do:
  • If you are in the Porepunkah area, you must follow instructions of emergency services at the scene.
  • Anyone with information is asked to call 000 immediately, or contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 333 or www.crimestoppers.com.au.
If you are outside the warning area:
  • Avoid the broader Porepunkah area.
  • Follow roadblocks and traffic diversions.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Road closures may change at short notice. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website for updates on road closures: traffic.transport.vic.gov.au.
This message is being issued by Victoria Police. 

The next update is expected by 31/08/2025 06:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency app
  • VicEmergency Facebook or Twitter
  • Victoria Police Facebook or Twitter
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • if you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

  • Victoria Police advise that the search for armed offender Desmond Freeman (Filby) continues in the broader Porepunkah area.
  • It is recommended that people travelling to Bright, Falls Creek or Mount Hotham avoid travelling through Porepunkah and instead, travel via Happy Valley Road at C534 and the Kiewa Valley Highway.

  • Anyone who has any information is asked to contact Crime Stoppers on 1800 333 000 or www.crimestoppers.com.au.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Broadford.
  • There is a building waste fire on Davis Road, Broadford.
  • Smoke may be visible from nearby roads and communities. 
  • CFA and Environment Protection Authority (EPA) are managing the incident.
  • This Advice replaces the Advice issued at 6.39 PM, Monday 25 August. 
There is currently no threat to the community, but you should continue to stay informed and monitor conditions.
What you should do:
  • If you smell smoke, stay indoors and close windows and doors. 
  •  Older adults, children, pregnant women, and people with heart/lung conditions should avoid heavy outdoor activity. 
  •  People with asthma should follow their action plan and keep medication nearby.
Impacts in your area:
  • CFA will be regularly monitoring the area.
  • Smoke, unless heavy, is unlikely to impact water. 
  • Rainwater in tanks that have not been affected by ash and debris from a fire, and where no taint or odour is present, can be used for normal purposes.

This message was issued by Country Fire Authority.

The next update is expected by 02/09/2025 06:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Community Newsletter:

https://files-em.em.vic.gov.au/public/CommNews/Fact-Sheets/2025-08-28_Newsletter__Davis__Rd__Broadford.pdf?v=202508271426

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfires)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility:

The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.

  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.  
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.location: Macalister River upstream of Lake Glenmaggie
properties.webBody:
This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for Macalister River upstream of Lake Glenmaggie. 

  • Minor flooding no longer expected at Licola.
  • Elevated river levels are occurring along the Macalister River upstream of Lake Glenmaggie but minor flooding is no longer expected at Licola.
  • Rainfall totals of 10-23 mm have been recorded in the catchment in the last 48 hours. 
  • No significant rainfall is forecast across the catchment for the next few days.
Macalister River upstream of Lake Glenmaggie:

  • Minor flooding is no longer expected along the Upper Macalister River at Licola.
  • The Macalister River at Licola peaked below the minor flood level. 
  • The river is currently at 2.21 m and steady, below the minor flood level. 
  • The Macalister River at Licola is expected to remain below the minor flood level (2.70 m).
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.
Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks to Euroa.

Minor flooding possible at Euroa Saturday evening.

Moderate rainfall has been observed in the Seven Creeks catchment which has resulted in creek level rises.

Seven Creeks to Euroa:

  • The Seven Creeks at Euroa is currently at 2.11 meters and rising, below the minor flood level. It may peak near the minor flood level (2.50 m) Saturday evening.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides â€“ be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/08/2025 01:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact the National Relay Service and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the King River at Docker rd.

Minor flooding is possible at Docker Road Bridge overnight Saturday into Sunday. 

Moderate rainfall has been observed across the Ovens and King catchments which has caused river level rises, with minor flooding possible along the King River at Docker Road Bridge.

King River:

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently at 2.61 m and rising, below the minor flood level and may peak near the minor flood level (3.70 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/08/2025 12:10 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
